<subSubSection id="C34B87E3FF931D79FF00DE0AFE37FD15" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF00DE0AFE37FD15" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF00DE0AFEC1FDAE" bold="true" box="[151,273,613,638]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Relatively small, blackish, hairy with predominantly black marked hind wings (
<figureCitation id="136AC8EDFF931D79FB32DE0AFB38FDAD" box="[1189,1256,613,637]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1397,1420]" captionTargetBox="[194,1411,395,1326]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,375,1371]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., habitus of the male holotypus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280801/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB4CDE0AFB38FDAD" box="[1243,1256,613,637]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); wings oval in shape with sparse venation; pterostigmata short; apical area with two rows of cells; anal area normally developed; ectoproct without projections.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34B87E3FF931D79FF5EDEBEFE42FB81" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF5EDEBEFF3AFBFD" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF5EDEBEFE8AFD3A" bold="true" box="[201,346,721,746]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Description.</emphasis>
Head broader than the thorax; genae hairless; vertex narrower than one eye in dorsal view; eyes large, divided by a transverse furrow; antennae hairless, a little shorter than the forewing. Wings with relatively sparse venation; forewing elongated, narrow, noticeably longer than the hind wing; pterostigma distinct, divided by a single cross vein; apical area beyond the vein Sc+R with few, large cells, disposed in two rows; sector of the radius with few cross veins (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE75DF0EFE20FCA9" box="[482,496,865,889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="5.0">5</number>
) between the latter and the radius; Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC3BDF0EFC6AFCA9" box="[940,954,865,889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC5DDF0EFC03FCA9" box="[970,979,865,889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A reaching Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB17DF0EFB59FCA9" box="[1152,1161,865,889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
a origin from Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FAC5DF0EFA8CFCA9" box="[1362,1372,865,889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
; hind wing oval, heavily marked, Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE61DFEAFDD3FC4D" box="[502,515,901,925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FDABDFEAFD96FC4D" box="[572,582,901,925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A long, reaching Rs origin from R; anal area normally extended (Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FAFEDFEAFAA8FC4D" box="[1385,1400,901,925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
A). Thorax hairy; legs short and slender. Abdomen hairy, shorter than wing (albeit only slightly shorter than the hind wing). Male ectoproct simple, without projections (
<figureCitation id="136AC8EDFF931D79FD7BDFA2FCE4FC35" box="[748,820,973,997]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[233,1378,186,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,179,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., male abdomen in situ, lateral view. 3. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., A, male genitalia, lateral view; B, male genitalia everted, lateral view; C, male genitalia, dorsal view; D, male genitalia, ventral view. Ectoproct (ep), parameres (pa), gonarcus (gs), pulvini (pv)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FCB4DFA2FCE4FC35" box="[803,820,973,997]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
); sternite IX cuneiform (
<figureCitation id="136AC8EDFF931D79FBCFDFA2FB4EFC35" box="[1112,1182,973,997]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[233,1378,186,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,179,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., male abdomen in situ, lateral view. 3. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., A, male genitalia, lateral view; B, male genitalia everted, lateral view; C, male genitalia, dorsal view; D, male genitalia, ventral view. Ectoproct (ep), parameres (pa), gonarcus (gs), pulvini (pv)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB07DFA2FB4EFC35" box="[1168,1182,973,997]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
D); gonarcus thin and curved; paramere elongated, tubular; pelta present; pulvini small, slightly protruding, with short gonosetae (
<figureCitation id="136AC8EDFF931D79FAF3DF9EFF74FBFD" captionStart="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1954,1977]" captionTargetBox="[233,1378,186,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,179,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 &amp; 3. 2. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., male abdomen in situ, lateral view. 3. Agadirius trojani gen. et sp. nov., A, male genitalia, lateral view; B, male genitalia everted, lateral view; C, male genitalia, dorsal view; D, male genitalia, ventral view. Ectoproct (ep), parameres (pa), gonarcus (gs), pulvini (pv)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Figs. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FF00D87AFF74FBFD" box="[151,164,1045,1069]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF5ED856FE42FB81" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" box="[201,402,1081,1105]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34B87E3FF931D79FF5ED832FC07FB49" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF5ED832FC07FB49" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF5ED832FE80FBA5" bold="true" box="[201,336,1117,1141]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new genus is named in honor of the Moroccan city of 
<collectingCountry id="F34694F8FF931D79FBBED832FBA9FBA5" box="[1065,1145,1117,1141]" name="Morocco" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Agadir</collectingCountry>
, capital of the region of Souss–Massa–Draâ where the species was collected. Gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34B87E3FF931D79FF5ED8CAFEE5FA45" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF5ED8CAFEE5FA45" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF5ED8CAFE81FB6E" bold="true" box="[201,337,1189,1214]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Comments.</emphasis>
The new genus belongs to the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FCCED8CAFC20FB6D" box="[857,1008,1189,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ascalaphinae">Ascalaphinae</taxonomicName>
(split eyed owlflies); the scale-like ectoproct and the shape of the genitalia is consistent with the tribe Ascalaphini as defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FB2DD8A6FF35FAD5" author="Tjeder" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="Tjeder, B. &amp; Hansson, C. (1992) The Ascalaphidae of the Afrotropical Region (Neuroptera). 2. Revision of the tribe Ascalaphini (subfam. Ascalaphinae) excluding the genus Ascalaphus Fabricius. Entomologica Scandinavica, Supplement, 41, 171 - 237." type="journal article" year="1992">
Tjeder and Hansson (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FF08D882FF0CFAD5" box="[159,220,1261,1285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. This tribe is not well delimited because it is based both on plesiomorphic characteristics, as also underlined by the same authors, and on a study of only Afrotropical taxa. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FCE2D97EFB60FAF9" author="Tjeder" box="[885,1200,1297,1321]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="Tjeder, B. &amp; Hansson, C. (1992) The Ascalaphidae of the Afrotropical Region (Neuroptera). 2. Revision of the tribe Ascalaphini (subfam. Ascalaphinae) excluding the genus Ascalaphus Fabricius. Entomologica Scandinavica, Supplement, 41, 171 - 237." type="journal article" year="1992">
Tjeder and Hansson (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FBFAD97EFB77FAF9" box="[1133,1191,1297,1321]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
considered the tribe equivalent to the tribe Suhpalacsini van der 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FD2ED95AFC9FFA9D" author="Weele" box="[697,847,1333,1357]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="van der Weele, H. W. (1909) Ascalaphiden, monographisch bearbeitet. Collections Zoologiques du Baron Edm. de Selys Longchamps, Catalogue Systematique et Descriptif, fasc. VIII, 1908, 1 - 326. [date of distr.: 5. I. 1909 cf. Cowley, J. (1937) The dates of distribution of the fascicles of the &quot; Catalogue des collections de Selys Longchamps. Journal of the Society for the Bibliography of Natural History, 1, 31 - 32.]" type="journal article" year="1909">
Weele, 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC83D95AFC9FFA9D" box="[788,847,1333,1357]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1909.0">1909</number>
</bibRefCitation>
. The situation is even more complicated by the homonymy between Ascalaphini 
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FD83D935FD82FAA1" box="[532,594,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FDCBD936FC58FAA1" author="Tjeder" box="[604,904,1369,1393]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="Tjeder, B. &amp; Hansson, C. (1992) The Ascalaphidae of the Afrotropical Region (Neuroptera). 2. Revision of the tribe Ascalaphini (subfam. Ascalaphinae) excluding the genus Ascalaphus Fabricius. Entomologica Scandinavica, Supplement, 41, 171 - 237." type="journal article" year="1992">
Tjeder and Hansson, 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FCC7D936FC58FAA1" box="[848,904,1369,1393]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
and Ascalaphini Lefèbvre 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB28D936FB27FAA1" box="[1215,1271,1369,1393]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1842.0">1842</number>
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FB68D935FAEEFAA1" box="[1279,1342,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">sensu</emphasis>
van der 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FF00D912FEE1FA45" author="Weele" box="[151,305,1405,1429]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="van der Weele, H. W. (1909) Ascalaphiden, monographisch bearbeitet. Collections Zoologiques du Baron Edm. de Selys Longchamps, Catalogue Systematique et Descriptif, fasc. VIII, 1908, 1 - 326. [date of distr.: 5. I. 1909 cf. Cowley, J. (1937) The dates of distribution of the fascicles of the &quot; Catalogue des collections de Selys Longchamps. Journal of the Society for the Bibliography of Natural History, 1, 31 - 32.]" type="journal article" year="1909">
Weele (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FF7BD912FEF9FA45" box="[236,297,1405,1429]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1909.0">1909</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34B87E3FF931D7AFF5ED9CDFBDBFEEF" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D79FF5ED9CDFCE6F9F5" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FF5ED9CDFE68FA69" authority="Lefebvre, 1842" authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[201,440,1441,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Puer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF5ED9CDFED0FA69" box="[201,256,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Puer</emphasis>
Lefèbvre, 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE17D9CEFE68FA69" box="[384,440,1441,1465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1842.0">1842</number>
</taxonomicName>
is the only genus superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FC34D9CEFBC1FA69" box="[931,1041,1441,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FC34D9CEFBC1FA69" box="[931,1041,1441,1465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Agadirius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A216B501FF931D79FB8BD9CDFB56FA69" box="[1052,1158,1442,1466]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and is traditionally, but erroneously, included in the tribe Ascalaphini Lefèbvre 
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FC84D9A9FC81FA0D" box="[787,849,1478,1501]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">sensu</emphasis>
van der 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FC20D9AAFB81FA0D" author="Weele" box="[951,1105,1477,1501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="van der Weele, H. W. (1909) Ascalaphiden, monographisch bearbeitet. Collections Zoologiques du Baron Edm. de Selys Longchamps, Catalogue Systematique et Descriptif, fasc. VIII, 1908, 1 - 326. [date of distr.: 5. I. 1909 cf. Cowley, J. (1937) The dates of distribution of the fascicles of the &quot; Catalogue des collections de Selys Longchamps. Journal of the Society for the Bibliography of Natural History, 1, 31 - 32.]" type="journal article" year="1909">
Weele (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB9AD9AAFB99FA0D" box="[1037,1097,1477,1501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1909.0">1909</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, as also stated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC0A999FF931D79FAB5D9A9FE44F9D1" author="Aspock" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" refString="Aspock, U. &amp; Aspock, H. (1987) Wiederentdeckung von Puer maculatus (Olivier) in Europa (Neuropteroidea: Planipennia: Ascalaphidae). Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Osterreichischer Entomologen, 39, 5 - 11." type="journal article" year="1987">
U. Aspöck and H. Aspöck (
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FED9D986FE5BF9D1" box="[334,395,1513,1537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1987.0">1987</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. In fact, both its external and internal genitalia are similar to those of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FA83D986FA45F9D1" box="[1300,1429,1513,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FA83D986FA45F9D1" box="[1300,1429,1513,1537]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Ascalaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is evident that a tribal revision of 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FDBFDA62FD6FF9F5" box="[552,703,1549,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascalaphidae</taxonomicName>
is needed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEED468FF931D7AFF5EDA5EFBDBFEEF" blockId="1.[151,1437,613,2006]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,319]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
The genitalia of the genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FD98DA5EFDADF999" box="[527,637,1585,1609]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FD98DA5EFDADF999" box="[527,637,1585,1609]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Agadirius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A216B501FF931D79FD1EDA5DFD23F999" box="[649,755,1586,1610]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FCA6DA5DFCB8F999" box="[817,872,1586,1609]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Puer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FCA6DA5DFCB8F999" box="[817,872,1586,1609]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Puer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show a plesiomorphic, simplified configuration, characterized by the absence of valuable diagnostic features. However, the difference in wing shape and venation are remarkable and comparable to that observed at genus level throughout the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FBC9DA16FB29F941" box="[1118,1273,1657,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascalaphidae</taxonomicName>
. The forewing of 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FF20DAF2FEF5F965" box="[183,293,1693,1717]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF20DAF2FEF5F965" box="[183,293,1693,1717]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Agadirius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A216B501FF931D79FEB8DAF1FE48F965" box="[303,408,1694,1718]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is characterized by sparse venation, the cross veins are relatively few and sparse and the cells are large; four branches originating from Rs; Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC95DAAEFCDFF909" box="[770,783,1729,1753]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC88DAAEFCF9F909" box="[799,809,1729,1753]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A just reach Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC70DAAEFC20F909" box="[999,1008,1729,1753]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
a origin from Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB2CDAAEFB15F909" box="[1211,1221,1729,1753]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
. The hind wing of 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FF00DA8AFED5F92D" box="[151,261,1765,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FF00DA8AFED5F92D" box="[151,261,1765,1789]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Agadirius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is oval in shape, reaching its maximum depth at the same height of the origin of Rs from R; the costal area is straight with 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE15DB66FE4EF8F1" box="[386,414,1801,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="13.0">13</number>
cross veins between C and Sc; 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC99DB66FCC8F8F1" box="[782,792,1801,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A runs far from the edge of the wing, is slightly curved towards it and has long, curved anal cross veins (Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FD6ADB42FCDCF895" box="[765,780,1837,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
A). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF931D79FCCFDB41FC5EF895" box="[856,910,1838,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Puer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF931D79FCCFDB41FC5EF895" box="[856,910,1838,1861]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Puer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the forewing appears relatively narrow due to the almost straight posterior edge with a slightly pronounced axillary lobe; much denser venation; five branches originating from Rs; Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE32DB1AFE63F85D" box="[421,435,1909,1933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE54DB1AFE1CF85D" box="[451,460,1909,1933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A well exceeding Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FD2BDB1AFD15F85D" box="[700,709,1909,1933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
a origin from Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FC1FDB1AFC42F85D" box="[904,914,1909,1933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
. The hind wing of the latter genus is a peculiar shape, reaching its maximum depth after the origin of Rs from R; the costal area is sinuous, narrower in the middle, with less than 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FEAADBD2FE89F805" box="[317,345,1981,2005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="10.0">10</number>
cross veins; 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FE67DBD2FE2AF805" box="[496,506,1981,2005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
A is very close to the wing margin, runs parallel to it and to Cu 
<number id="3D99C64FFF931D79FB4CDBD2FB38F805" box="[1243,1256,1981,2005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
for much of its length and has very short anal cross veins (Fig. 
<number id="3D99C64FFF901D7AFD23DCF8FD14FF7F" box="[692,708,151,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="4.0">4</number>
B). Moreover the pterostigma of 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF901D7AFBAFDCF7FB74FF60" box="[1080,1188,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trojani">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF901D7AFBAFDCF7FB74FF60" box="[1080,1188,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">A. trojani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is divided by a single cross vein while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF901D7AFEE6DCD2FE77FF04" box="[369,423,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Puer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF901D7AFEE6DCD2FE77FF04" box="[369,423,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Puer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is divided by two or three cross veins The wings of 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF901D7AFB9CDCD2FB92FF04" box="[1035,1090,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Puer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF901D7AFB9CDCD2FB92FF04" box="[1035,1090,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Puer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be highly distinctive with the posterior straight margin of the forewing corresponds well with the sinuous shape of the costa of the hind wings; this may be linked to flight dynamics. On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName id="4C51AFEBFF901D7AFCFCDD6BFC09FECC" box="[875,985,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Agadirius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925087AFF901D7AFCFCDD6BFC09FECC" box="[875,985,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Agadirius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by a much more typical wing shape and venation, despite some modifications due to small dimensions.
</paragraph>
